rottles abuse. The bucket maximum is set to the same value as the per-minute rate, which means a rested client can send that many requests immediately. What it cannot do is sustain a rate above the refill speed. A burst that fits within `bucket_capacity` on a single instance is expected behavior: the client was idle, accumulated a full bucket, and spent it.

**Before concluding the limiter is working as designed, rule out the multi-instance case first.** Each instance maintains its own in-memory bucket state — they do not share a counter. With 3–5 instances running behind the load balancer, a client whose requests spread across instances can exhaust a full bucket on each one independently. In the worst case — five instances, requests distributed evenly — a client can push through 5x the intended per-minute limit without any single instance registering a violation. Pull the configured limits and check instance distribution to distinguish the two cases:

```bash
# Fetch configured limits
ratelimit-cli config get --client <client_id>

# Sample recent traffic by instance
ratelimit-cli requests --client <client_id> --window 5m --by-instance
```

The three fields that matter in the config output: `bucket_capacity` is the maximum burst a single instance will allow, `refill_rate_per_second` is the sustained ceiling, and `refill_seconds` is how long a full refill takes. If the burst volume stays within `bucket_capacity` on every individual instance, no single node recorded a violation — whether that reflects intended system-level behavior depends on whether requests were concentrated on one instance or spread across several. If requests are spread across instances and the aggregate exceeds `bucket_capacity`, that's the multi-instance problem — escalate to the owning team with the `--by-instance` output attached.</draft>

